{{main|List of mountain peaks of Canada}}
{{see also|List of the most prominent summits of Canada|List of the most isolated major summits of Canada}}

[[Image:Mount Logan.jpg|thumb|400px|[[Mount Logan]] in the [[Saint Elias Mountains]] of [[Yukon]] is the [[topographic elevation|highest]] [[summit (topography)|peak]] of [[Canada]].]]

The following sortable table comprises the '''19 [[Summit|mountain peaks]] of [[Canada]] with at least {{convert|4000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}} of [[elevation]] and at least {{convert|500|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}} of [[topographic prominence]]'''.<ref name=major>This article defines a significant summit as a summit with at least {{convert|100|m|1|abbr=off|comma=5}} of [[topographic prominence]], and a major summit as a summit with at least {{convert|500|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}} of topographic prominence.  All summits in this article have at least 500&nbsp;meters of topographic prominence.  An [[Ultra-prominent peak|ultra-prominent summit]] is a summit with at least {{convert|1500|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}} of topographic prominence.</ref>

The [[summit]] of a mountain or hill may be measured in three principal ways:
#The [[Elevation|topographic elevation]] of a summit measures the height of the summit above a [[Geoid|geodetic sea level]].<ref name=range>If the elevation or prominence of a summit is calculated as a range of values, the [[arithmetic mean]] is shown.</ref>
#The [[topographic prominence]] of a summit is a measure of how high the summit rises above its surroundings.<ref name=prominence>The [[topographic prominence]] of a summit is the [[Elevation|topographic elevation]] difference between the summit and its [[Topographic prominence#Definitions|highest or key col to a higher summit]].  The summit may be near its key col or quite far away.  The key col for [[Denali]] in [[Alaska]] is the [[Isthmus of Rivas]] in [[Nicaragua]], {{convert|7642|km|0|abbr=off|comma=5|sp=us}} away.</ref><ref name=range/>
#The [[topographic isolation]] (or radius of dominance) of a summit measures how far the summit lies from its nearest point of equal elevation.<ref name=isolation>The [[topographic isolation]] of a summit is the [[great-circle distance]] to its nearest point of equal elevation.</ref>

Five major Canadian summits exceed {{convert|5000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}} elevation, 11 exceed {{convert|4500|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}}, the following 19 summits exceed {{convert|4000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}}, 41 exceed {{convert|3500|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}}, [[List of the major 3000-metre summits of Canada|67 exceed {{convert|3000|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}}]], and 125 exceed {{convert|2500|m|0|abbr=off|comma=5}} elevation.

__TOC__{{clear}}

==Major 4000-metre summits==
{{GeoGroup|section=Major 4000-metre summits}}
{{main|List of the highest major summits of Canada}}
{{see also|List of the major 3000-metre summits of Canada}}
Of these 19 major 4000-metre summits of Canada, 17 are located in Yukon and two in British Columbia.  Five of these summits lie on the international Yukon-Alaska border and one lies on the international British Columbia-Alaska border.
