{{redirect|Mike Batty|the footballer|Mike Batty (footballer)}} {{Use dmy dates|date=June 2013}} {{Use British English|date=June 2013}} <!-- [[File:Michael Batty - Saint-Dié-des-Vosges 20131005-03.jpg|thumbnail|Michael receiving the [[Lauréat Prix International de Géographie Vautrin Lud|Vautrin Lud Prize]], 5 October 2013]]This is a comment -->
{{Infobox person |name = Mike Batty |image = Mike-batty21.tif |caption = Michael Batty |birth_date = {{birth date and age|df=y|1945|01|11}} |occupation = British Urban Planner & Geographer }}
'''Michael Batty''' [[CBE]], [[Fellow of the British Academy#Fellowship|FBA]], [[Fellow of the Royal Society|FRS]], [[FAcSS]] (born 11 January 1945) is a British [[urban planner]] and [[geographer]], and a Professor in [[The Bartlett]] at [[University College London]] .<ref name="casa">{{cite web |url = http://www.ucl.ac.uk/bartlett/people/?school=casa&upi=JMBAT23 |title = Mike Batty's CASA UCL Web Page | accessdate = 2014-10-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.ucl.ac.uk/hr/services/kpis/index.php?id=ALL |title = UCL Academic Honour KPI Summary Table | accessdate = 2014-10-28}}</ref> He has been Director—now Chairman—of the [[Centre for Advanced Spatial Analysis]], set up when he was appointed to UCL in 1995.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.casa.ucl.ac.uk/ | title = UCL CASA Web Home Page | accessdate = 2011-04-18}}</ref> His research and the work of CASA is focused on computer models of city systems. He was awarded the [[William Alonso]] Prize of the [[Regional Science Association]] in 2011 for his book Cities and Complexity, the same prize a second time for his book The New Science of Cities in 2017-2018, the University Consortium GIS Research Award in 2012,<ref>{{cite web |url = http://ucgis.org/ucgis-awards/michael-batty |title = University Consortium for Geographic Information Science Mike Batty Web Page |accessdate = 2014-10-28 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20141028172442/http://ucgis.org/ucgis-awards/michael-batty |archivedate = 28 October 2014 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> and the [[Lauréat Prix International de Géographie Vautrin Lud]], the so-called 'Nobel for geography', in 2013. In 2015, he was awarded the [[Gold Medal (RGS)|Founder's Medal]] of the [[ Royal Geographical Society]] and in 2016, the Gold Medal of the [[Royal Town Planning Institute]] (RTPI). He also received the Senior Scholar Award of the Complex Systems Society in September 2016.
== Education == Michael Batty was born in Liverpool and educated at Northway County Primary School<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.northway.liverpool.sch.uk | title = Northway County Primary School | accessdate = 2014-11-03}}</ref> from 1950 to 1956 and then at [[Quarry Bank High School]] for Boys from 1956 to 1962. He went to the [[University of Manchester]] (1962-1966) where he studied [[Town and Country Planning]] gaining the BA degree with First Class Honours in 1966. His PhD is from the [[University of Wales]], Institute of Science and Technology in 1984. The thesis on Pseudo Dynamic Urban Models<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.casa.ucl.ac.uk/PhD.pdf | author = Batty, M. | date = 1984 | title = Pseudo Dynamic Urban Models | accessdate = 2014-10-28}}</ref> was made available online in 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.spatialcomplexity.info/archives/747 | title = Research, Write, Type, Submit, Pass, and 30 Years Later... | author = Batty, M. | date = 2012 | accessdate = 2014-10-28}}</ref>
==Current Affiliations== *Professor of Planning in the Bartlett School at [[University College London|UCL]] where he is Chairman of the [[Centre for Advanced Spatial Analysis]](CASA). From 1995 to 2003, he was Professor of Spatial Analysis and Planning holding a joint appointment between the Department of Geography and the Bartlett School of Planning at UCL. In 2003 Mike became Bartlett Professor of Planning, succeeding [[Peter Hall (urbanist)|Professor Sir Peter Hall]]. * Visiting Distinguished Professor at [[Arizona State University]].<ref>{{citation |url = http://geoplan.asu.edu/batty |title = Arizona State University Mike Batty Web Page |accessdate = 2011-11-22 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131230233041/http://geoplan.asu.edu/batty |archivedate = 30 December 2013 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> * Honorary Professor at [[Cardiff University]].<ref>{{citation | url = http://www.cardiff.ac.uk/cplan/contactsandpeople/stafflist/a-b/batty-michael-professor.html | title = Cardiff University Mike Batty Web Page | accessdate = 2011-11-22}}</ref> * Distinguished Vice Chancellor's Professor, Chinese University of Hong Kong * Distinguished Professor, Hong Kong Polytechnic University * Editor of the journal Environment and Planning B: Planning and Design.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.envplan.com/epb_contacts.html | title = Environment and Planning B: Planning and Design: Editorial Board Web Page | accessdate = 2011-11-22}}</ref>
==Academic career== He began his academic career in the [[University of Manchester]] in 1966 where he was appointed an Assistant Lecturer in [[Town and Country Planning]]. He then spent 10 years at the [[University of Reading]] as Research Assistant, Lecturer and Reader in [[Geography]]. During this time he spent one year as a Visiting Assistant Professor of Transport Planning in the Department of Civil Engineering in the [[University of Waterloo]], Ontario. He moved to the [[University of Wales]] Institute of Science and Technology (now the [[University of Cardiff]]) in 1979, where he was Professor of [[town planning]]. During this time, he acted as Head of Department, and Dean of the Faculty of Environmental Design. In 1990, he moved to direct the US [[National Science Foundation]] (NSF) [[National Center for Geographic Information and Analysis]] (NCGIA) at the [[University at Buffalo, The State University of New York|State University of New York at Buffalo]] (SUNY-Buffalo) where he was a Professor of [[geography]].
He has held several visiting appointments in computing, engineering, planning, and geography at the following Universities: [[University of Illinois]]; [[University of Melbourne]]; [[University of Hong Kong]]; [[University of Bristol]]; [[University of Michigan]]; and he currently has visiting appointments at [[Cardiff University]] <ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.cardiff.ac.uk/cplan/about-us/staff/michael-batty | title = Cardiff School of Planning and Geography Mike Batty Web Page | accessdate = 2014-10-28}}</ref> and [[Arizona State University]].<ref>{{cite web |url = http://geoplan.asu.edu/batty |title = Arizona State University School of Geographical Sciences and Urban Planning Mike Batty Web Page |accessdate = 2014-10-28 |deadurl = yes |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20131230233041/http://geoplan.asu.edu/batty |archivedate = 30 December 2013 |df = dmy-all }}</ref>
== Scholarship == His research has focussed on the development of analytical methods and computer models for simulating the structure of cities and regions. Early work involved aggregate land use transport models which are summarised in his first book ''Urban Modelling''.<ref>{{citation | url = http://www.casa.ucl.ac.uk/urbanmodelling/ | title = Urban Modelling: Algorithms, Calibrations, Predictions | author = Batty, M. | date = 1976 | accessdate = 2014-10-28}}</ref> After this early work, he focused on more visual representations of cities and their models and some of these were represented in his second book ''Microcomputer Graphics''.<ref>{{citation | url = https://www.amazon.co.uk/Microcomputer-Graphics-M-Batty/dp/0412285401 | title = Microcomputer Graphics | author = Batty, M. | date = 1987 | accessdate = 2014-10-28}}</ref> With [[Paul Longley]], he published ''Fractal Cities''.<ref>{{citation | url = http://www.fractalcities.org | title = Fractal Cities | author = Batty, M., Longley, P. | date = 1994 | accessdate = 2014-10-28}}</ref> This work established the idea that cities might be regarded as the outcome of self-similar [[fractal]] processes generating structure from the bottom up. His work on complexity theory in urban analysis and planning is the focus of his book ''Cities and Complexity'',<ref>{{citation | url = http://mitpress.mit.edu/books/cities-and-complexity | title = Fractal Cities | author = Batty, M. | date = 2005 | accessdate = 2014-10-28}}</ref> a summary of which is available on his ComplexCity web site.<ref>{{cite web | title = A Science of Cities | url = http://www.complexcity.info | accessdate = 2014-10-28}}</ref> His most recent book ''The New Science of Cities''.<ref>{{citation | url = http://www.complexcity.info/about-the-book/ | title = The New Science of Cities | author = Batty, M. | date = 2013 | accessdate = 2014-10-28}}</ref> ties many of the ideas together, developing the notion that it is flows rather than locations that are key to an understanding not only of cities but also the processes for their design and planning.
He has edited several volumes, most recently ''Agent-Based Models of Geographical Systems''<ref>{{citation | url = http://www.gisagents.org/2011/11/new-book-agent-based-models-of.html | title = Agent-Based Models of Geographical Systems | editor = Batty, M. |editor2=Heppenstall, A.J. |editor3=Crooks, A.T. |editor4=See, L.M. | date = 2011 | accessdate = 2014-10-28}}</ref> and ''Virtual Geographic Environments''.<ref>{{citation | url = http://esripress.esri.com/display/index.cfm?fuseaction=display&websiteID=206&moduleID=0 | title = Virtual Geographic Environments | editor = Batty, M. |editor2=Lin, H. | date = 2011 | ISBN = 9781589483248 | accessdate = 2014-10-28}}</ref>
Details of his publications are available from his curriculum vita<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.complexcity.info/files/2013/08/BATTYCV.pdf | title=curriculum vita | author = Batty, M. | date = 2014 | accessdate = 2014-11-03 }}</ref> and on his personal web pages.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.spatialcomplexity.info/ | title=spatialcomplexity weblog | author = Batty, M. | accessdate = 2014-11-03 }}</ref> <ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.complexitycity.info/ |title = the science of cities weblog |author = Batty, M. |accessdate = 2014-11-03 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>
==Memberships and Fellowships== Learned Societies: He has been elected a [[List of Fellows of the Royal Society elected in 2009|Fellow of the Royal Society (FRS) in 2009]], a [[Fellow of the British Academy]] in 2001, a Fellow of [[Academy of Social Sciences]] in 2001 and a [[Fellow of the Royal Society of Arts]] in 1982.
Professional Institutes: He has been a Member and now Fellow of the [[Royal Town Planning Institute]] since 1971, and the [[Chartered Institute of Logistics and Transport]] since 1984.
==Past Roles== He has recently acted as: [http://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/appsi%5Cdefault.htm Member of the Advisory Panel on Public Sector Information - APPSI], Chair of the [[ESRC]] Census Advisory Committee, and a Member of the UK [[Research Assessment Exercise]] (RAE) 2004-2009 Geography Panel.
At Cardiff, he was a Member of the Computer Board for British Universities and Research Councils, now [[Jisc|JISC]] (1988–1990), a Member of the SERC ([[Science and Engineering Research Council]]) Transport Committee (1982–1985), Chair (1980–1982), then Vice-Chair (1982–1984) of the ESRC ([[Economic and Social Research Council]]) Environment and Planning Committee, and Chair of the Conference of Heads Of Planning Schools (CHOPS) 1986-1980.
== Honours == {| ! Year awarded ! Name of Award ! Awarding organisation ! Reason for award |- | 2016 | CSS Senior Scientific Award | [[Complex Systems Society]] | He has pioneered the idea of cities as complex systems,as well as for his leading role in the conformation of the Science of Cities that combines a wide spectrum of disciplines ranging from Statistical Physics, Mathematics, Architecture and Engineering, to Social Sciences and Economics.)<ref>{{citation | url = http://cssociety.org/news/47 | title = Complex Systems Society News | accessdate = 2016-09-22 }}</ref> | | |- | 2013 | [[Lauréat Prix International de Géographie Vautrin Lud|Vautrin Lud Prize]] | | | |- | 2010 | Alonso Prize | [[Regional Science Association]] | Cities and Complexity (MIT Press, Cambridge, MA, 2005)<ref>{{citation |url = http://mitpress.mit.edu/catalog/item/default.asp?ttype=2&tid=10627 |title = MIT Press Cities and Complexity Understanding Cities with Cellular Automata, Agent-Based Models, and Fractals Book Web Page |accessdate = 2011-04-18 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110720074620/http://mitpress.mit.edu/catalog/item/default.asp?ttype=2&tid=10627# |archive-date = 20 July 2011 |dead-url = yes |df = dmy-all }}</ref> |- | 2004 | [[CBE]] | | Services to geography |- | 2002 | Innovation | [http://www.agi.org.uk/ Association of Geographic Information] | |- | 1999 | Sir George Back Award | [[Royal Geographical Society]] | Contributions to national policy and practice in planning and city design |- | 1998 | Technological Progress | [http://www.agi.org.uk/ Association of Geographic Information] | |}
