{{Unreferenced|date=March 2007}}
'''Suomenselkä''' is a [[drainage divide]] in western [[Finland]]. Roughly {{convert|500|km|mi}} long and {{convert|30|-|50|km|mi}} wide, it is marked by an ensemble of northeast-southwest oriented [[moraine]]s parallel to the [[Gulf of Bothnia|Bothnian]] coastline.  Rivers flowing west from Suomenselkä drain to the Gulf of Bothnia and the lakes in the east drain to the [[Gulf of Finland]].  Historically, this very sparsely populated region separated [[Ostrobothnia (region)|Ostrobothnia]] from the southern and eastern lake regions of Finland. The landscape is marked by moraines, [[esker]]s, [[swamp]]s and [[forest]]s and is difficult to cultivate or settle in.  Because it contains some of the few remaining patches of [[old-growth forest]] in southern Finland, it is one of the few remaining habitats for [[Finnish Forest Reindeer]] (''Rangifer tarandus fennica'').  

